review.reviewBody: I'm not one for reviews, but these boots exceeded expectations. I'm replacing a pair of 9 year old "fit like a glove" boots, and have purchased multiple pairs of high-end boots before finding these. They are true to size, great craftsmanship, and comfortable out of the box. They are warm and waterproof, making kids' sports a breeze. They are wide enough to fit a typically "wide" foot, but narrow enough for an average width. They're beautiful, and rugged, all in one wonderfully priced package. Here's to strutting in style and comfort for the next ten years! Kamik's for the win! The question is: what color will my second pair be?
review.name: My New Faves

review.reviewBody: I bought these boots for winter trail riding and everyday wear, and they have been perfect. They are very comfortable and warm, and kept my feet dry even when walking through snow, slush, and mud at the barn, and provided good traction as well. I love the side zipper which allows for easy on and off without having to undo the laces. I've worn them under bootcut jeans and over skinny jeans and they look good with both. They'll be cute with skirts/dresses too. I'm usually a 9.5 in winter boots and a 9 in other shoes and needed a 10 in these. My daughter typically wears an 8.5-9 and she kept the size 9's. So if you are a half size I'd recommend going up to the next whole size.
review.name: Functional and stylish boots

review.itemreviewed: Mt. Baker II GORE-TEX Mitten - Men's
review.reviewBody: 100% of the insulation is in the liner. Leading to no dexterity (which is the point of a liner). The outer is water proof, but after a walk in the neighborhood at 19F, they're stiff and cold. My hands were in a true liner and they warmed up as soon as I took the outer off. The large liner by itself doesn't keep my hands warm pumping gas. And because they're so thick, I'm sure they'd sweat out on a winter hike which is why I bought them. I would never take them on a hike or ski outing. So disappointed.
review.name: Worst mitts I own

review.itemreviewed: Mt. Baker II GORE-TEX Mitten - Men's
review.reviewBody: Amazing gloves. Been wearing these since I was kid snowboarding in Washington. 20 years later still ordering them for East coast seasons. Super warm, super dry. Easy to get on and off fast. The liners are amazing on their own. The shell is also great to throw over lighter liners if your touring and run into weather. But put these liners on with the shell and this glove keeps you warm in well below freezing temps and dry and happy as can be.
review.name: 3 Gloves in 1

review.itemreviewed: Mt. Baker II GORE-TEX Mitten - Men's
review.reviewBody: These are very durable and great in cold weather. My hands stayed warm in even single degree weather.
review.name: Great in cold weather

review.itemreviewed: Mt. Baker II GORE-TEX Mitten - Men's
review.reviewBody: Size Little smaller than table i guess. I sized up and comfortable. (I like it bit roomy) Pros Modular system 3L goretex Completely Removable liner Wrist & cinch seal Long & wide opening Cons /or could be improved Bulky Rigid Shell inner surface is not comfortable Shell outer surface is prone to collect dirts a little Wrist seal is not easy to use (rigid) Cinch cord is not easy to use with mitts on There is no liner option depending on temperature. Overall Best heavyduty modular mitts on the market!
review.name: Few modular glove system on the market

review.itemreviewed: Mt. Baker II GORE-TEX Mitten - Men's
review.reviewBody: Perfect gloves for temps below 10 degrees. If I'm walking on the trail and having to work, these can almost be too warm.
review.name: Perfect for the Alaskan temps

review.itemreviewed: Mt. Baker II GORE-TEX Mitten - Men's
review.reviewBody: I've owned about 3 pairs of these over the last 30 years and they are hands-down the best glove in terms of keeping your fingers warm whether shoveling the driveway, snowboarding, or climbing a mountain. Well worth every penny!
review.name: Best glove.... Hands down!

review.itemreviewed: Mt. Baker II GORE-TEX Mitten - Men's
review.reviewBody: light wear after one use on the outer shell which isn't great. worked well in cold (single degree F) conditions + wind chill. I'm a bit concerned they're not capable of super cold Winter days here in CO but they are definitely a step up from most other gloves
review.name: mostly impressed

review.itemreviewed: Mt. Baker II GORE-TEX Mitten - Men's

review.name: Thorough, durable design.

review.reviewBody: Shoes have good grip (as usual for sportiva shoes) but rubber is too thin. Were worn very quickly - 3 month or so climbing 3 times per week in the gym.
review.name: Not durable

review.reviewBody:
I bought the Kubo to use as a more comfortable option than my performance fit Scarpa Vapors for a multi-pitch heavy trip. They exceeded all of my expectations, to the point that my Vapors saw zero action on the trip. The Kubo's were super responsive. They handling edging + smearing exceptionally well. As an added bonus, they weren't excruciating in the occasional foot jam. Loved that they were comfortable enough to keep my feet happy all route, day and trip long without feeling sloppy. 

In a world of $200+ climbing shoes the Kubo is a total gem. 

For reference: I bought the Kubos in a 37, the same size as my older model TC pros (also sized on the more comfortable side of things). The Kubos seem to fit slightly more snuggly, which was perfect for me. Haven't noticed much (if any) stretch.
review.name: exceeded all expectations

review.reviewBody:
When I had worn out my first pair of climbing shoes, I was looking to upgrade from a neutral to a slightly more aggressive shoe. I had tried on several shoes (and by several I mean 20+), but none of them fit the way I needed them to. And definitely none were as comfortable as my initial scarpa force vs. BUT the la sportiva kubos have just the right amount of performance edge and comfort that I was looking for. I can trust my feet on smaller holds and it hugs my feet just right. I did size down a tad, so a little tight right out of the box, but it's growing on me. Comfort is a priority for me. And the nice colors help too!

Street size : 6
Scarpa Force Vs : 37
La Sportiva Kubos : 35.5
review.name: Great Intermediate Shoe

review.reviewBody:
I've been looking for a cycling shoe with flat sole that easily slides into my toe-clip equipped pedals. I have wide feet (EE) and a Morton's neuroma which can be very painful with tight shoes. These fit just fine. They are quite comfortable to walk in too.

The only negative thing is that in humid weather your feet may get a bit warm as the shoe is made of a durable material that doesn't breathe all that well. This is a quibble. 

I bought my first pair last summer from a local bike shop. I've worn that pair every day since. When I saw Backcountry stocked them, I bought a second pair.
review.name: At last a real touring shoe

review.reviewBody:
I have a wide foot and these are the only flat pedal MTB shoe that is actually shaped like a ?real?human foot. The toe box on these is wider than basically any other MTB flat pedal shoe on the market, believe me I tried them all on. Even Specialized highly praised 2FO roost.  I wear a size 10 US in Chuck Taylors and got these in a size 45EU which is around a size 11 US. If you have a normal foot the sizing is probably dead on for you.
These aren?t the stiffest shoe, but they aren?t soft by any means. The soles on mine are finally falling apart after two years of riding. The grip is great though no problems there. The shoes work great with my Kona Wah pedals and my Shimano XT wide pedals. 
They are definitely worth the coin I just wish there was more shoe options for wide footed riders.
review.name: My go to flat pedal shoes

review.reviewBody: The Hikelite 18 is incredible for travel, day hikes, daily commuting via bike, and more. It fits under an airplane seat, has hydration bladder capability for day hikes, includes a chest and waist strap to secure the bag to you when biking, and it is the perfect size. I cannot recommend this pack enough.
review.name: The best backpack I have ever owned

review.reviewBody: Someone wrote that the Hikelite is lacking a handle loop. IDK, mine has one. As I do with all my backpacks, I put a large S-biner on it, so I can hang it, it even hooks over 40 cm thick stall doors so I don't have to set my pack down. I also riveted thick vinyl sheeting on bottom so that it can be set down on icky bathrooms or muddy ground..... Osprey take note! Bottom of packs should have waterproof vinyl sheet!
review.name: Mine has a loop handle..... I put large S-biner to hang Hikelite on thick stall doors

review.reviewBody: The Hikelite 18 is perfect for me, no downsides! Fits my Apple M2 16" (someone wrote it doesn't fit their 14" laptop) with no need for sleeve as it is protected by the wire frame.... plus small photography drone + controller + 3 batteries in a Solo rectangular gear pack (looks like softside lunch box), Hikelite is great for day-trekking photo shoots. The whole Hikelite 18 then drops perfectly into an Eddie Bauer 22" rolling half-hardshell duffel for all-in-one travel (dusty busrides on dirt roads). Before boarding aircraft I take out the Hikelite to easily fit underseat (and use laptop), while the now-shrunken duffel can fit in limited overhead bin space.
review.name: Great for travel and business mix!!!

review.reviewBody: My husband and I each got one of these packs and tested them out in Banff National Park. They were the perfect size for a Nalgene bottle in the side pocket, 2 extra bottled waters in the other side pocket, a raincoat, jacket, packed lunches, and camera gear inside. The pack is so breathable and felt really lightweight on our hikes. We even did a via ferrata climb and nothing fell out of the side pockets and it didn't feel like I even had a pack on. Highly recommend for day hikes!
review.name: Love this pack!

review.reviewBody: Bought this last year for a trip and so glad I did. It help up two water bottles, jackets, and a bunch of snacks. I also got a great deal because it was on sale. Very sturdy and love the breathable backing so you don't easily sweat during hot muggy days. I can fit a tablet, but it was too small for my 14" laptop. All in all, great backpack for day travel or a personal item to carry and fits nicely under the seat cabin on the plane.
review.name: Great day pack for travel

review.reviewBody: I loved everything about this pack--the color, the light frame that keeps it off your back, weight, and size. Unfortunately, I ended up returning this pack as the strap was too thick for me to install a camera clip I use while hiking; I really wanted it to work as it is such a well designed pack for day hikes!
review.name: Well designed pack!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The side pockets perfectly fit a Nalgene. The whole pack fits my back perfectly and the vent actually does its job! Definitely recommend this one for a day hike:)

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Excellent product. Incredibly light despite the wire frame. I never carried backpacks on our hikes as I hate a sweaty back. Have used it on long hikes on back to back days in the Swiss Alps, both sunny warm days, and forgot I was carrying a backpack, no sweaty back. Found myself bragging to my wife about finding the product.
review.name: Excellent product. Incredibly light despite

review.name: Love it

review.reviewBody: Best in class. I'm between L/XL so I have one of each. Light weight, breathable. I use it for those early tee times or on the bike, The hood works well under the helmet.
review.name: Nice Bit of Kit

review.reviewBody: The feel is smooth and comfortable. The fit is as good as the feel. Can’t wait to get more.
review.name: Great hoodie

review.reviewBody: Love the fit, function and look- this hoody is my go to. Great weight for cool weather running and hiking. Layers well with a light shell to keep wind/rain at bay.
review.name: Go to active hoody

review.reviewBody: Light weight to wear for sun protection, but also has kept me warm if the sun goes away and a chilly wind picks up on the multi. Comfy material and I like the colors.
review.name: Solid All Around Shirt

review.reviewBody: Love the fit since I am tall and long-limbed; the length of sleeves and torso are great. The medium is just right for me being 6'1" with a ~39-40" chest, 168 lbs. Fit is a little slimmer but not tight by any means but not loose with a bunch of extra flapping fabric.
review.name: Great sun shirt

review.reviewBody: I have purchased two of these for the past year of guiding, and have been thoroughly impressed. I developed a tear that worried me due to the stretchy nature of the fabric, and I did not think that it would hold a patch well. However, after a year of abuse, the small tear has not grown any larger! The only con that another expert has mentioned is that this fabric is quite hot and heavy when soaked in a humid/rainy environment.
review.name: Alpenglow Pro Shines like the Alpenglow on your Summit Approach

review.reviewBody: This shirt is great! With sun protection and a good overall fit, I wish I had more stars to rate. It keeps you cool you when it’s hot, a nice addition to help you ventilate. With this hoody, more adventures do await!
review.name: A Great Adventure Shirt

review.reviewBody: I had this sun shirt for about 2 seasons and it was awesome at first. It for just right and was great for climbing and general sunny desert activities. I also used it for saltwater fly fishing. I don’t know what happened but the salty air and water wrecked this shirt and any stretch properties it had failed. I put it on at the beginning of this season after fishing in it all last summer and it was as if someone traded my medium for a 2 XL. The sleeves hand down 4 or 6 inches below my fingertips, the bottom goes well halfway to my knees when it used to end right at the waist. I actually thought someone was playing a joke on me and swapped it out with one 3 sizes bigger. It was great while it fit but the elastic properties are gone and it is not a good sun shirt for me in a salty environment.
review.name: Stretches out.

review.reviewBody: Huge fan. Nice and stretchy, moisture wicking, and well fitting. Hood stays on well. Wore it everyday on a 5 day backpacking trip with a cap underneath. Felt great.
review.name: Had One, Bought Another

review.reviewBody: Very warm and sturdy. Perfect for upper-Midwest winters!
review.name: Solid boots

review.itemreviewed: Shellista V Mid WP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Cute boots and they are comfortable enough. Defiantly not the warmest boot I have owned, but they do a decent job at keeping my feet warm. Also, they will trip you up if you do not have the laces around the hooks at the top of the boot.
review.name: Cute Boots

review.itemreviewed: Shellista V Mid WP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: These boots are great! Waterproof, warm, and durable. I walk my dog several miles per day in these. The only reason these are getting 4 instead of 5 stars is the lace hook on the inside of the boot. It's slightly too far forward, so if your legs brush by each other, the lace from the opposite boot gets stuck together. If you have any forward momentum (I.e. walking quickly) and you will fall face first. I was able to clamp them all the way down with pliers.
review.name: Great, other than lace hook

review.itemreviewed: Shellista V Mid WP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I feel twice from these two hooks getting hooked together. That could kill someone on the ice or snow. Horrible design flaw.
review.name: I wish they would just make shellista talks again

review.itemreviewed: Shellista V Mid WP Boot - Women's

review.reviewBody: I agree with other that: 1) it is not cast iron, but painted, and it chips easily; 2) the logotypes and text smear off easily with oil and grease; but also that I either received a defective stove or a defective regulator because it chokes either a few minutes into cooking and immediately and banging the regulator seems to help, but then if I only use one burner and then turn on the other, the first one shuts off, then if I use both and then turn one off but come back to both, the same, one shuts off. Also, the anti spill ridge is nice but the spill still gets into the holes for the grates. It is very nice that it is not like a camping stove and it is HEAVY, which is nice.
review.name: Nice and Weird, Expensive and Good Looking

review.reviewBody: The cooking topooks cast iron but is a sprayed on coating. The only cast iron is in the grill grates. They are made of cast iron attatched to steel rings with screws. Otherwise stove works great. Dials allow very precise flame adjustments, on tbe other hand only 10,000 BTU.
review.name: Stove top is not cast iron. It is sprayed on

review.reviewBody:
I recently (6 weeks ago) purchased a Coleman PEAK1 two burner camp stove. I have only used my stove on two trips and am disappointed that the right side burner will not ignite. After reading some reviews on this page, I see that this seems to be a common
Issue. Dear Coleman customer service, please provide some advice and assistance on this  known issue. On a positive note, Coleman have designed a functional, easy to clean and stylish camp stove neatly packed in a smart protective carrying case.
review.name: Nice camp stove if it would ignite!
comment:
Hello!

We are also sad that your stove stopped working after your two trips. This is certainly not the experience we want you to have. our feedback is highly appreciated and valued by the business, and we will make sure that your insights are shared.

Please contact us directly to further assist you. You can access our contact form online by selecting "contact us" from the question mark logo in the upper right corner of the page.

review.reviewBody: I have to agree with the majority of the people that have rated this stove anyone else was rated at less than five stars absolutely has no clue what they're doing. I have wiped mine down repeatedly with all kinds of cleaners etc the finish on this product is second to none it's well applied powder coat and it is solid and I mean solid is not cheap tinsy little metal like some of these old camp kitchens. I especially love the burners cooking in the wind they've held up beautifully I'm able to boil water at no time at all and the heat that's produced by those burners is fantastic it's the last stove I think I'll ever buy I've got a trailer and I've got a Jeep and it's going in both of them!
review.name: The Best Stove Ever!

review.reviewBody: Take this in our caravan for outdoor cooking. It does however need a griddle for use as a BBQ. What do you recommend we use? Is the Triton or hyperplane griddle suitable? There is not a griddle accessory specific to this stove.
review.name: Portable and practical

review.reviewBody: Great stove. Well-built, but a bit heavy. I like the soft-sided carrying case. Not sure how durable it will be over time.
review.name: Great stove.

review.reviewBody: Only one burner worked with the automatic starter , kinda heavy . Did not have issues once lit and was very windy at the end of the lake. Nice case included.
review.name: It boiled water

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This Coleman 2 burner stove is amazing. I love the fact that I can cook anything on it and anywhere. It's huge so I can cook with my large skillets and Dutch oven.  It has a carrying case for easy transport to different locations. We are a bosting, camping, picnicking family so this works for all the above
review.name: Love it!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This Coleman burner stove makes cooking while camping so much easier for us. It doesn't take up a lot of space compared to what we've been using.  It comes in a carrying case and it only weighs 12 lbs.  This stove also has a rotary ignition making it easier to turn on. We also didn't experience any problems while cooking with it.  I personally love that we can use this stove during emergencies, outdoors only of course, if the power ever goes. out.
review.name: Easy To Cook With

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I bought these after signing up to be a volunteer in Central Park.. first time wearing ankle non-fashion boots! and 65 years old-- 
I tried them on in a store that had a mock, resin? boulder to climb up and down on.
They felt the best of 3-4 other pair/brands I tried, though that is a subjective thing- and quite brief.
So I cannot compare them to any other hiking boots' performance..

But they have been excellent- so far. I've probably worn them 6-9 hours 'in the field'! They feel substantive, protective, and sturdy.
review.name: first time hiking boots and Merrell wearer..

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I live and hike mostly through large rock formations near my home in Prescott AZ.  Many of these rocks are pretty steep but, with this shoe I have the utmost confidence I can leap from rock to rock without slipping. Inclines and declines, the grip is solid. Also, a very comfortable shoe to wear. This is my third pair of this shoe and I plan on sticking with the brand and style.
review.name: Best gripping sole ever!

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: True to size and very comfortable.  I wear a 10 and bought a 10.5 women’s for comfort while hiking. I would recommend a .5 up.
review.name: Very comfortable. Order a 1/2 size up

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: These hikers are great. I have arthritic feet and Merrell is my go-to solution. These shoes have the support I need, are accurately sized and super cute at the same time. Score!
review.name: Super cute hikers

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Love that they’re comfortable, right from the start. No need to break them in.
review.name: Terrific comfy boots

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I purchased these to replace a pair of Merrell hiking boots that had finally fallen apart after 20 years and hundreds of miles. They are the same great, sturdy but light-weight boots that I love. They didn't require any break in time and I have happily worn them through some wet and slippery conditions with zero complaints.
review.name: I still really love my Merrells

review.itemreviewed: Moab 3 Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Got these for a hiking trip to Zion national park. Straight out of the box, comfortable and stayed that way thru all the hikes! Very impressed with the grip on the trails, especially the steep parts up and down.
review.name: Highly recommend!

review.reviewBody: Love these boots! I hike with my dogs all summer and snowshoe all winter. They are perfectly comfortable right out of the box!! I’ve been wearing this brand for 15 years. When one pair wears out ( usually I get a couple years) I purchase another pair.

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] As someone that is on their feet all day, this product has been amazing. It has made my recovery much quicker and is very effective. I like that it is portable and I can take it anywhere I need, and so far has been very durable. The low noise level allows me to use it at night while family is sleeping. It is a bit on the pricey side, but it’s definitely an investment and worth it in my opinion.
review.name: Great recovery tool

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Oh my God, I can’t believe I received this complementary of influenster! The boots was definitely effective because I walk a lot comfortable easy to put on and does the job perfectly. The level is not nothing crazy it felt so good. I highly recommend.
review.name: Best Ever

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I’ve been running regularly, and for the past 2 months, these JetBoots have been a total game-changer for my recovery. They are highly effective in relieving muscle fatigue, incredibly comfortable to wear, and very portable, so I can use them anywhere. The durability is impressive, and the low noise level makes the experience even more enjoyable. Perfect for runners who need fast and efficient recovery!
review.name: Effective, Comfortable, and Perfect for Post-Run R

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Help alleviate soreness with your muscles! They apply pressure to the legs so if you don’t like feeling that sensation then you might no enjoy. Noise is tolerable
review.name: Nice

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This Jetboot is a portable, wireless compression boot system designed for quick and effective muscle recovery you can use at home. With four adjustable pressure settings and FastFlush Technology, it inflates and deflates in 60 seconds to optimize circulation and reduce fatigue. The boots are lightweight, easy to use with built-in controls, even my grandma, my mom who don’t have much experience with this type of new technology device can easy to put it on, sit back and relax. The only thing is the price is way too high, not everyone who needs will be affordable to own it. But if you can afford it, it will turn out to a good investment, one can be used for the whole family.
review.name: Good  investment but not afforadable for anyone…

review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] First off, the packaging is spot on, it’s easy to open and unfold, and easier to fold up to store in the bag it comes in. 
They come in different sizes and I think for me these were a bit tall so my husband who had had a bad ankle injury and circulation issues used it to review as well. 

It’s interesting when you put them in, it’s almost like a blood pressure cuff that gets tighter and then releases in sections from your foot to your upper thigh.  It has different levels to try so we both tried them all. 

It’s not too loud, so we were able to enjoy a show while using the Thera Body Jet Boots. 

As someone who is always on the go and someone who has had surgery on his foot, ankle, the circulation aspect is quite impressive.  Furthermore, normally after a workout, the next day you can feel sore-ish. This seems to help minimize the ache. (If that makes sense). 

Now add the Thera gun to the knots and you feel like an entirely new person. 

We have used these several times and they pack up and store easy, and also travel well too. 

It’s like having a circulation massage therapist on call. 

We both would recommend.
review.name: Give your legs the recovery they deserve while rel

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The Therabody JetBoots Prime are the best and most optimal way to boost your recovery! When it comes to the lower half of the body it gets put through the wringer. But the JetBoots Prime have you covered on all sides with maximum comfort and convenience! This essential part of your recovery fits nicely into a draw string bag that you can take with you on the go anywhere! Even on the go the JetBoots Prime are quick and easy to deploy and use. The power and noise level of the pumps are impressive to say the least! These are the most technologically advanced set or recovery boots on the market. A must for efficient and fast recovery!
review.name: Prime Time!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I’ve never tried a product like this before so I wasn’t certain what to expect, I’m pleasantly surprised! It inflated in no time and the pressure was very relaxing, like the effect of a weighted blanket all around your legs. My only gripe is the sizing can be tricky, just make sure you get their size reference before buying!
review.name: Relaxing

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I love this product and so does my boyfriend. I’m a treadmill walker & yoga girl, and he is a firefighter that lifts weights. Different physical activities, but we both find the therabody jet boots to be an amazing recovery and self care product. The different settings allow you to adjust the level of pressure, to achieve different results. The boots fit a wide variety of sizes as shown in the video. They zip on easily and fold up once deflated to fit into the bag they come with. Definitely recommend. I’ll also be lending these to a friend that is having surgery coming up, and this is a great way to promote blood flow if you’re laid up in bed! They’re also very quiet when in use.
review.name: A great gift for yourself or a loved one!

name: JetBoots Prime

review.reviewBody: I got these pants in anticipation of starting a season of trail work. They held up through an entire season of rock work, which was pretty impressive. The material was relatively breathable for being so durable. Only complaint is the zipper pocket which i had to replace, and the button that closes the waist finally popped out on me on the second to last day. I'll likely be getting these again.
review.name: Survived 6 months of trail work

review.reviewBody: These pants are over sized! I purchased a size 6 and they were about 3 sizes too big on me! I have purchased North face hiking pants in the past. Same Size 6. They fit me normal. My size has not changed. They have changed the design of them. They were thicker and bulkier. Not comfortable at all. I will never purchase North Face products again. I wish they would stop changing the styles and how clothing fit for women.

I find the khaki color does not drape/lay as well as the black one does, and it tends to show more lumps & bumps Still, these are very functional, easy pants for all kinds of adventures.

review.reviewBody: I'm using them for a trip to Italy in which I will carry a backpack so I need to minimize the amount of clothes I bring. These are good because they're shorts, capris and pants. What I don't like is that the shorts are too short and do not have patch pockets like the men's style of these pants have. They're also fairly heavy. Would be nice if they were lighter weight fabric.

review.itemreviewed: Riff Endless Promise Sleeping Bag: 15F Down - Women's
review.reviewBody: I have no complaints, though it may be because this is the first high quality down bag I've owned, upgrading from a 15 year old synthetic bag. So far I have no real complaints. I have not used the bag in extreme conditions, so I can't comment on the bag's limits. The thermo gills are nice, though they don't release as much heat as I expected.
review.name: Excellent bag

review.itemreviewed: Riff Endless Promise Sleeping Bag: 15F Down - Women's
review.reviewBody:
Nemo continues to impress! This sleeping bag is everything a camper could want/need. One of the most important things to me when I'm buying a piece of gear I plan to use for months on end, is that it is:
1. Ethically sourced and made
2. Doesn't introduce my body to harmful chemicals (PFAS free water repelant, RDS certified!)
3. Recyclable
4. Easily Repairable
5. Light Weight (3lbs 4oz)
6. Is made to last
VICTORY!
I'm obsessed with the pillow pocket on the interior, YKK zippers, and the draft collar to keep the heat in! In the past, my hair would get caught in the Velcro of the draft collar on other sleeping bags but NEMO chose to go sans Velcro leaving all my hair in tact! 

The rating is for 15F but I believe it could be used even colder, though I haven't tested that yet!

The side zips offer the perfect way to cool off if it gets too warm and the color is extremely cute (I have the green). 

I love that there is a Regular and Long option. Why carry around that extra weight if you don't have to? Stuff sack too?! THANK YOU NEMO!
review.name: Simply the BEST!

review.itemreviewed: Riff Endless Promise Sleeping Bag: 15F Down - Women's
review.reviewBody: If you feel like sleeping in a mummy bag is like being trapped after a long day on the trail, get this sleeping bag.  It is lightweight, compacts down small, and provides so many comfy features like a blanket fold and pillow pocket.  You can even cool down during the night by opening the chest zippers.
review.name: Perfect for backpacking

review.itemreviewed: Riff Endless Promise Sleeping Bag: 15F Down - Women's
review.reviewBody: My wife gets cranky and claustrophobic in mummy bags. The extra room was awesome, and she was warm all night.

review.itemreviewed: Riff Endless Promise Sleeping Bag: 15F Down - Women's

review.itemreviewed: Riff Endless Promise Sleeping Bag: 15F Down - Women's
review.reviewBody: Incredibly warm for shoulder season frosts, zippers are functional and toe box is very insulated. However, it's narrow. On my side or back, there is tension of the bag on my shoulders or arms, which feels constricting enough that I keep it unzipped. There's no way I can adjust positions without it unzipped. The 'long' version adds room to the hip and shoulder, but then you have the extra deadspace at your feet if you're not close to 6'. The Women's Disco version has +5 inches in the hip and +2 in the shoulder. For reference, I am athletically built at 5'6 and 140 lb. Would give a 5/5 if this bag had just a bit more room to it.

review.itemreviewed: Compact MSL Pact Inflatable Stand-Up Paddleboard - 2024
review.reviewBody:
I just received my 11' compact and was blown away by how small of a package it is, including the pump and the paddle.  

We have two of the 10' 6" Ride's and we have two different model years of the 12' 6" Voyager from Red, I have been very pleased with all of them, so much so that I wanted to try out one of their compacts. 

We like to travel and I like to bring a board with us when I can.  Hawaii, even Europe, along with future trips to New Zealand and Australia.  I know you can hire/rent boards at different places, but I find that a hassle and something I don't want to deal with.   

This 11' compact is going to make bringing a board along so much easier,  When I unrolled it I was shocked at how much more pliable it is, then, having it be able to fold onto itself to make the entire unflated package super compact, the backpack bag is half the size of a normal bag from Red and the board itself is super light in comparison to any of the other boards we own from Red.  
I was looking at the 12' compact, but it was too similar to the Voyagers we already have, the 11' kinda hits another sweet spot and lengthens out our quiver of boards.   I live in the PNW and surfing isn't really a major factor here, neither is where we stay in Hawaii, in discussing the ability of being able to ride some small waves is what pushed me into purchasing the 11'. 

I am so impressed with the 11' compact, that in the future, I might very well get another in an even shorter length.  Maybe even getting another 11'.  It tracks well, it has a decent glide for my weight, I think it would do even better for someone like my wife, but to have a board that is such a small package should push a smaller person, or a woman into loving a compact over a normal inflatable.   I find I am the donkey when my wife and I go anywhere, she can lift the other boards, but she has trouble navigating any steps, or corners carrying them, so that usually falls on me, with this 11' compact, it is not going to be the case at all, the weight is so much better that her attention of carrying it, or getting fatigued will be minimal. 

If you like to travel and bring your board, these compacts will blow your mind in their construction and portability.  Plus, being able to pull out a full sized paddle that comes in 5 pieces is also remarkable.  Not the lightest paddle when coming from higher end ones, but to be able to travel and have it all in the backpack is pretty amazing. 

The new Titan pumps are way better than the first generation Titan pumps as well, getting up to 20psi is super easy and something a smaller person can easily do. 

The only wish I have.. I wish the bag came with wheels and a pull up handle for pulling the thing through an airport, or over pavement.  I like the backpack, but sometimes you would like to be able to pull something along instead of having it on your back.   

I get super excited for travel when I think of the board, I want to SUP Venice Italy, which is on my bucket list, I think of so many other places I have been, that if I would have had a SUP with me, I would have had even fonder memories of those places.
review.name: The comparison is kinda mind blowing

name: Compact MSL Pact Inflatable Stand-Up Paddleboard - 2024

review.reviewBody:
I do a lot of road riding, and have tried a lot of different lubricants. I'm pretty impressed with this on my road bikes. I followed the directions, and cleaned the chain prior to use ( I used 91% rubbing alcohol from Walgreens and a toothbrush to just scrub the junk out), and then applied fairly liberally, wiped dry and allowed the chain to sit as recommended before riding. Before riding, I touched the chain to make sure it was dry, and found it to have the same feeling as the lube from a new chain; while riding, I found it was quiet for 200+ miles. some were wet miles, but the majority were dry. Where I live in central NC, there is some dust that accumulates on every ride. It has done a good job with keeping a lot of it from sticking. what does stick, has wiped of quite easily. I'm on the 3rd application and the experience has been the same from the first (I clean again before re-coating since it really doesn't take that much time).   Not sure how this does for MTB riding, but for road, I find it to be quite solid. 

P.s. the light is a good toy for my kids...
review.name: Good Stuff

review.reviewBody:
I couldn't be more impressed with this lube. Compared to other lubes I've used in the past, this lasts at least a few rides (in dry conditions). If you apply it at least an hour before a ride (3-4 hours is recommended) it will penetrate perfectly and have you pedaling with a silent drivetrain. And if you follow the instructions, it really doesn't attract dirt/dust much. A quick wipe down with an all purpose cleaner every few rides and re-applying and you'll be able to go weeks or months without having to deep clean your drivetrain. 

Super impressed and will continue buying and using this lube for mountain and road riding.
review.name: Fantastic Lube

review.reviewBody:
Being a lube aficionado and someone who believes in a perfectly clean, maintained, tuned and well running drivetrain, I cannot get behind this lube.

I've read tons of feedback from forums as well as scientific testing from our friend over at ZeroFrictionCycling and the results for this lube are more or less spot on: it's just not that good.

The biggest issue is chain noise and the lube itself either washing off too easily, quickly, not penetrating deep enough and simply being either too viscous or not formulated well for daily riding in general conditions.

I find Dumond Tech Lite to be an outstanding lube that I've been using for years. Rock 'n Roll Gold is also a star of the show with perhaps more frequent applications and better suited for gravel vs. road (but RNR is amazing for road as well).

The goal of a great lube is to: keep your drivetrain well lubed, reduce friction, reduce noise and prevent dirt as best as possible.

While the Muc Off C3 prevents dirt, its noisy and doesn't last. And I'm riding in bone dry California weather.

3/5 for me, I'll keep playing with it on another bike but not a premiere lube especially for the price. The UV light is a cool gimmick though :)
review.name: Not impressed

review.reviewBody: I've never really noticed a difference when using different lubes. However after applying g this lube I noticed a much smoother and quieter ride. Definitely will continue to use this!
review.name: Surprisingly good!

review.reviewBody: This is way better than Finish Line Dry Lube. My chain absolutely purrs with this on. You want to make certain that you get all the extra lube off or it will still attract trail dirt. I am sold on Muc-Off and will be recommending this for sure. Also, I like that the small cap on the applicator screws on. I put this in my frame bag (inside a zipped plastic bag) and had no issues with any leaking.
review.name: Better than other top rated dry lubes

review.reviewBody:
I am just getting back into bicycle riding after a 20+ year absence.  My typical ride is ten miles in about an hour. 

This jacket is a great windbreaker for cool fall mornings.  I'll wear wool underneath on chiller mornings, and whatever if the weather is warmer. 

Fit is snug,  but comfortable.  This would be the first jacket to use as Fall sets in, and the last jacket before Summer temperatures makes an appearance. 

A windbreaker,  no padding.
review.name: Nice windbreaker!

review.reviewBody:
Pearl Izumi's Quest Barrier Convertible Jacket is an updated version of their old ELITE Escape Barrier Convertible Jacket, but with even more features and design tweaks.  The feature set of this jacket at this price point is outstanding, to say the least.

First and foremost this converts from a jacket to a vest very quickly.  Having the ability to go between the two is great for changing weather conditions.  Start a ride on a crisp spring morning, but know it's gonna warm up a fair bit by the end of your ride?  This jacket/vest is for you.

On the back there's a zippered back pocket, and on the front there are two front pockets as well.  These front pockets are an addition that the old ELITE Escape Barrier Jacket did not have.  They can be used to hold stuff-- or they can just be opened to allow some air in to let you vent and stay the right temperature.  You can also do this by unzipping the jacket up from the bottom via the two-way zipper.

The top half of the vest on the back is a mesh material, to help you breath under the windbreak material.  Breathability is often lacking on windbreaker style jackets, but not here.

Sizing is about what I'd expect from a relaxed-fit item in Pearl Izumi's catalog.  I wear a Medium in their standard or relaxed fit jerseys, and usually bump up to a Large in their Standard fit jackets to have room to layer.  I stuck with a Medium in this jacket, however, due to the relaxed fit.  I didn't want this vest and jacket to be too big on me, and with the relaxed fit the medium gives me enough room.

My ONLY complaint is the neck opening.  I mentioned elsewhere on another review that I have a bit of a thick neck, but this neck opening is ridiculously small.  In the previous ELITE Escape Barrier Jacket (standard fit, large), I had no problem zipping the jacket up all the way.  When I was trying this jacket, I bought both a medium and a large.  While I could zip the jacket up all the way on the large, it was TIGHT-- tighter than the large of the ELITE, while this jacket is relaxed and should be looser.  I'd have had to bump to an XL to get a good neck fit- which is ridiculous and not something I was going to do.  The Medium fits me fine elsewhere, so I'll just deal with not zipping the jacket up that last inch or so.  I truly don't know what Pearl was thinking here about the neck.  It makes no sense when comparing against other jackets in their lineup, both standard and relaxed, in both medium and large sizes.  This neck is clearly 1 size smaller than the rest of the jacket.  Period.

At the end of the day I'm not gonna knock the jacket a star for the neck, as I think everything else about it makes up for this one issue, and I personally have no issue leaving it slightly unzipped.  But PI... c'mon!
review.name: Feature packed barrier jacket

review.reviewBody: Purchased a PEARL IZUMI Quest Barrier Convertible Jacket to use on my gravel bike for cool or windy days.   The jacket fits well and to size.  I am 5' 8" and usually wear a large.  Jacket is very light.   My only complaint would be the elastic used in the wrist is a big snug so if you are wearing a watch or anything else on your wrists it may require a bit of a tug to pull the jacket off otherwise no complaints.
review.name: Quest Barrier Convertible Jacket!

review.reviewBody:
Fine pad. It is cheap. I have this and the duo for my home gym. Get the duo it is the same price per square foot of landing zone  and the duo is a more useful size with more features for carrying gear and better straps.

This pad is not firm. Lots of reviews say it is, mine is not. I am 140 lbs and I am using this in a garage climbing gym. It is good for that application. The hinge and the edges of this pad feel pretty soft due to the loose fitting cover and the fact that the foam is not bonded together. I might take it apart and glue the different layers together.  

I have a metolius magnum that is a firm pad. The metolious is much better quality. It has a tighter fitting cover and the foam is stiffer. Get this pad if you want the cheapest pad available, it is fine. It works. Get the duo it is a better value. Get a different brand if you want a stiff firm landing surface.
review.name: Fine

review.reviewBody: Its great, its decently thick when unfolded. Easy to carry around. I also use it as a chair of sorts when I am not using it outdoors.
review.name: Great crash pad

review.reviewBody:
I bought two of these for my home climbing wall and to boulder outside (normally sport climb but occasionally boulder). This has been an EXCELLENT pad. It has taken months of abuse and holds its form well.

We also use it as a sleeping mat in our tent at night (and actually use the lounge chair option) when car camping. I absolutely love this and will be buying two more of these for extra protection at the home gym. Great product and fun colors!
review.name: First Boulder Pad

review.reviewBody:
Solid all-around down jacket. It's at home both on the mountain or walking around the city. The fleece-lined pockets are a really nice touch, especially once your hands get really cold. It packs down fairly small and doesn't take up too much space in my pack. The hood is compatible at least with the climbing helmet, though I haven't tried a ski/snowboard helmet with it. 

It's a true-to-size fit - though a bit bulkier than other jackets I've worn.
Well-designed, lofty down, lots of good details, and just the right combo of sturdily made but not too heavy.
review.name: Great jacket!

review.reviewBody: Great fit and good quality. Seems warm and doesn’t have air cut through like some other puffies I’ve owned. Have been happy with all my previous purchases of BD jackets.
review.name: Great fit and good quality.

review.reviewBody: It is light in weight and warm for NYC spring and fall season. The fit is just right and the color of the jacket matched the advertisement.
review.name: outstanding product

review.reviewBody: Nice design, good finish a bit long on the sleeves for the size.
review.name: Very good

review.reviewBody: Nice entry into insulation layer. Found the outter material to be a little stiff for my taste and sizes run big, so I upgraded for the Approach Down BD layer.
review.name: Nice entry insulation layer

review.reviewBody:
For a 700 fill goose down the baffling dimensions make the shoulder loft unable to adequately keep in heat at even 45 degrees F.

The zipper is loud and not smooth feeing compared to similar products. 

The fit is comparatively large in the waist for a Medium making the annoying and breakable bungee drawstring necessary to keep heat in. You could leave the upper waist dimension the same but taper it in at the bottom…
Initial fabric water repellency is adequate. 
This is all compared to same caliber brands like Patagonia and Marmot. 
This puffy is fine for the price, just not good.
review.name: Average materials and craftsmanship for price

review.reviewBody: I wanted to like this jacket but it did not do it for me. The sleeves are too long and there is hardly any elastic on the cuff. So it just droops over my hands. They need to put a real Velcro closure on the cuffs. I also found the jacket too light and not warm enough for my needs in cold weather here in Northeast. This is more  a mid layer. I have an excellent Black Diamond Shell but this jacket disappoints.
review.name: Sleeves way too long

review.reviewBody: This is one of the best men's down hoodies on the market. The fill is thicker than most, but the cut of the fit doesn't make you look like the Michelin Man.
review.name: Excellent fit and comfortable warmth!

review.reviewBody: I needed a warm mid-layer coat for our trip to Peru - the Access Down Hoody was it. I was looking for the warmth of a sleeping bag but needed it to be packable and fit under my waterproof Shell jacket. This jacket did it all. It was super warm when I needed it, especially at night while sleeping in a mountain hut. It has an amazing front top pocket that is easily accessible with another layer on top. I love that the hood keeps my neck and head warm, and keeps the wind away. This is one great down puffer, great work Black Diamond.
review.name: Perfect for a Peruvian Pilgrimage!

name: BD Access Down Hoody - Men's

review.reviewBody: My hand size is usually L-XL. On a hunch I ordered XXL. They were initially tight enough that I was worried. However after the first ride or two, I am pleased with the size. They wear well.
review.name: Runs small but rides well

review.reviewBody: After two months of periodic use, both hands have a hole. There is also not a pull tab to remove them with your other hand. I would not buy them again.
review.name: Not great

review.reviewBody:
The gloves may fit, but I wouldn't know because the wrist opening is much too small to fit my hand through. My hand size falls squarely in the size small on the size chart. 
I thought Backcountry's return policy would pay for return shipping (it says prepaid), but that isn't the case. It's about $7 to return the online purchase. Not happy about it.
review.name: Don't Buy Too Small - Return Costs Money

review.reviewBody:
They are however nice gloves and I’m gonna use them since I purchased them with points. 

If I had ordered a size XL they wouldn’t have fit.
review.name: Comically Small even in XXL

review.reviewBody: Got an extra large and could barely get my fingers into the glove. Normally I take  large.
review.name: Absurdly Small

review.reviewBody: I like the style of construction. The palms and fingers fit really well, but the section at the wrist was so tight that it cut off circulation after about 10 minutes. I don't have thick wrists or anything odd. The wrist portion is just too narrow and the material doesn't stretch nearly enough for a normal wrist to be comfortable.
review.name: Almost good

review.reviewBody: Perfect draw to use for trad. Lightweight and strong. Put em on your rack!

review.reviewBody: As with every bd product, there is a level of durability and quality you expect when you purchase. This draw is perfect for trad and feel comfortable taking a whipper on them. The light wire beaners are perfect side for me, I don’t have extra large hands but not small either. Makes clipping natural and perfect. I also have order of mini wires on the way. review.reviewBody: Sturdy, simple, lightweight, and affordable. I’m loving these new draws.

review.reviewBody: Used these for last two years, happy to buy a new set. Durable.
review.name: Reliable

review.reviewBody: I love these drawers they are perfect for a long sport route or to take up a nice bolted multi pitch. I bought them because had them and I liked them so much. Would definitely recommend
review.name: Love my light wires

review.reviewBody: A decent lightweight quickdraw option, they have held up well over time. Not a lot of “wow” factor, but they get the job done. Not good draws for dogging on your project, but fine for a 40m pitch where you need 20+ quickdraws. I prefer to supplement with something like the Petzl Spirit which are heavier, but confidence inspiring and you can pull on them if need be.
Lightweight and easy to clip. I like them as a trad option, but also work well for cragging.
review.name: Solid Draws

review.reviewBody: I just got into climbing and these are great for starting out would definitely recommend. Solid build and feel great.
review.name: Great Product

review.reviewBody: These are very sturdy but very light weight. Work really well, 11/10
review.name: Super duper great

review.reviewBody: These are solid, but light draws. Really good for trad or alpine climbs where weight is a concern, but you still want bomber gear of course.
